## ðŸ“– Overview

Phlegm-Heat Obstructing the Lungs is a common, acute, and Excess pattern characterized by the accumulation of thick, viscous Phlegm combined with Heat in the Lungs. This obstruction impairs the Lung's function of dispersing and descending Qi, leading to a productive cough with difficult-to-expectorate yellow sputum, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

This pattern typically arises from two main pathways. It can develop from an external invasion of Wind-Heat that penetrates the Interior and combines with pre-existing Phlegm. Alternatively, it can form internally from factors like improper diet (excessive greasy, sweet, or spicy foods), smoking, or emotional stress leading to Liver Fire, all of which can generate Phlegm and Heat that settles in the Lungs. The presence of Heat is indicated by the yellow sputum, red tongue with yellow coating, rapid pulse, and other signs of heat like thirst and feverishness.

